    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.1-4_0001" />
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>10 Jan 18</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr Neihardt</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I began writing you some days ago, but was interrupted; and now, a few moments ago, I ran into Sterling, who tells me you are to be here the last of February. I am delighted that you are coming, and am looking forward to seeing you, with keenest pleasure &#8212; I am glad to hear
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.1-4_0002"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                
                that you are to appear at Stanford too. I have given a good deal of thought to your question &#8212; whether to read the lyrics or give your theory on the <unclear>epos</unclear> with illustrations from Hugh Glass and Three Friends. On the whole I think the latter would be better, and my friends all think so too. But I hate like the <unclear>dixie</unclear> to cut out the lyrics entirely. Can't you <unclear>bring</unclear> some of them in too? One reason 
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.1-4_0003"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                
                why I wouldn't read these exclusively is that we've recently had some poets here who did that, and it will serve to "place" you in distinction if you do the other, and bigger thing. Everybody's writing lyrics (such as they are &#8212; not in your class to be sure) but there's only one that can tackle successfully the epic. And, in a way, to me, one of the greatest qualities of the lyrics (yours) is that together they build up an epic, a subjective epic of the soul, of which Hugh Glass and Three Friends et al (when
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.1-4_0004"/>
                    <fw type="curatorial">4</fw>
                
                they shall be) form an objective expansion and extension. Do as thou will, and what thou willest shall be most cordially welcome. Only come, and give us a good sight and sound <unclear>of</unclear> you. Don't forget you're to come to Carmel, in spite of this club letter-head &#8212; I'm here only for a day. I go back to Pheidias tomorrow. God, you've simply got to like it! It's the whole <unclear/> race and all human nature. Write me just when you're coming. Make the Carmel trip whether before or after the Berkely and Palo Alto, as suits your convenience best &#8212;</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>&#192; Bientot, mon cher ami!</salute> 
                
                    <salute>A toi</salute> 
                    
                    <signed>Howard</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
